To complete the code, you need to use the `fork()` function, which is used to create a new process. The `fork()` function creates a new process by duplicating the existing process. The new process, called the child, is an exact copy of the calling process, called the parent, except for a few values that are changed in the child.

Here is the completed code:

```c
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main(){
    while(1) {
        //Create a new process
        pid_t pid = fork();

        if (pid == 0) {
            // This code is executed by the child process
            printf("I'm the child process with pid: %d\n", getpid());
        } else if (pid > 0) {
            // This code is executed by the parent process
            printf("I'm the parent process with pid: %d, my child has pid: %d\n", getpid(), pid);
        } else {
            // fork() returns -1 on failure
            perror("fork");
            return 1;
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Please note that this code will create an infinite number of processes because of the `while(1)` loop. Each child process will also create a new child process, and so on, leading to an explosion of processes. This is generally not a good practice and should be avoided in real-world applications.

Also, this code will not terminate even when the child process has completed its execution. If you want to terminate the parent process after the child process has finished, you can use the `wait()` function.

Here is a version of the code that includes `wait()`:

```c
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>

int main(){
    while(1) {
        //Create a new process
        pid_t pid = fork();

        if (pid == 0) {
            // This code is executed by the child process
            printf("I'm the child process with pid: %d\n", getpid());
            return 0;
        } else if (pid > 0) {
            // This code is executed by the parent process
            printf("I'm the parent process with pid: %d, my child has pid: %d\n", getpid(), pid);
            wait(NULL); // Wait for the child process to finish
        } else {
            // fork() returns -1 on failure
            perror("fork");
            return 1;
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This version of the code will wait for each child process to finish before creating a new one.

